column9: Description
Begin a DCE separator string.
End a DCE separator string.
The DCE range character. Used to represent ranges in DCE. See the wiki for more information.
Used to denote the union of two records. See the wiki for more information.
Begin a DCE number.
End a DCE number.
Substitution character for an unknown value.
Internal DCE calendar identifier for the Gregorian calendar.
Positive value (syntactical representation — This is not the + character)
Negative (syntactical representation — This is not the − character)
Drop back to the core sheet (no meaning in EDF)
Drop back to the enclosing sheet (no meaning in EDF)
Begins a DCE region (no meaning in EDF)
Processing use only (not for interchange)
Sometimes used as a visible word separator, e.g. in Anoej
Special casing considerations for Turkish
Special casing considerations for Turkish

This denotes content that is not "bound" (given a context of a page, etc. to be within) — in other words it is what a plain text file is to a word processing file with page formatting — content with no context given for presenting it

Also used as a line separator by Microsoft Word and Powerpoint which use it to contrast with the character used as a paragraph separator (sources: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/3380538/what-is-a-vertical-tab http://unicode.org/reports/tr13/tr13-9.html )
Begin Base 64 encapsulated UTF-8
End Base 64 encapsulated UTF-8

This Dc is used for embedding arbitrary keyed ID/data pairs in a document. Standard structure: Followed by base64-encoded data identifying a fragment, then Dc 202 (End keyed embed ID sequence), then by the base64-encoded fragment itself, then by Dc 201 (End keyed embed fragment).
See description for 200
See description for 200
Arbitrary binary data (base64 encoded, no semantic significance assigned to it)
See description for 203
Used to replace an incoming character whose value is unknown or unrepresentable in Unicode
Used to replace an incoming character whose value is not mapped to a Dc (document component)
Beginning of a document

This character instructs a terminal to move the cursor to the beginning of the line horizontally without advancing to the next line vertically. This character is not directly equivalent to ASCII line feed, because that is sometimes used for a combined new line and carriage return. For representing the ASCII line feed, use Dc 120.

This character instructs a terminal to advance to the next line vertically without moving the cursor to the beginning of the line horizontally. This character is not directly equivalent to ASCII carriage return, because that is sometimes used for a combined new line and carriage return. For representing the ASCII carriage return, use Dc 121.
Indicates that the following contents expect a graphical raster display output.
Indicates that the following contents provide resources (such as routine, class, or other definitions) for consumption by other documents.
Indicates that the following contents represent structured data.
Indicates that the following contents expect a character-based terminal display output.
Indicates that the following contents are designed to respond to a Web request (in a manner similar to a PHP or CGI script).

column2: Begin single-line source comment on current line
column9: Begins a comment that, when represented in EM (Ember Language source) format, should be displayed as a “#”-style comment. All characters except 248 and 255 will be ignored. Use 255 248 to represent 248 within the comment, and 255 255 to represent 255 within the comment.

column2: Begin single-line source comment on new line
column9: As with 247, but starting on a new line in the source form.
Terminates a comment region begun by 246 or 247.

column2: Begin block source comment on current line
column9: As with 248, but creating a “/*  */”-style block comment.

column2: Begin block source comment on new line
column9: As with 250, but starting on a new line in the source form.
Terminates a comment region begun by 249 or 250.
Indicates that a line break that would normally be present at this point in the source should be instead represented by a ;.
Indicates that the current logical line should be split into two physical lines in source form, joined using \.
Indicates that the following logical block of statements should be bundled onto a single line of the source, joined using ; and bundled using { and }.
Indicates that the next character should be ignored.
Send the specified string to the current output context
